    "summary": "Fermentation — the controlled microbial transformation of organic materials — was one of the earliest and most consequential food technologies developed by human communities. Evidence from the Near East and neighboring regions dating to around 7000–6000 BCE includes residues of fermented grain, fruit, and dairy products in ceramic vessels. The development of pottery in this period facilitated fermentation by providing suitable containers for the process.\n\nFermented beverages and foods offered significant advantages to early agricultural communities: they preserved nutritional value, reduced pathogens, and provided caloric density. Beer-like grain ferments and early wine production appear to have had both nutritional and social significance, with fermented drinks likely playing roles in communal gatherings and ritual contexts from very early on. The mastery of fermentation represents an intersection of empirical knowledge, material technology, and social organization that marked a significant advance in early human food culture.",
